---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="DailyDine Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[68ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono">
        <span>Work</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Case Study</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        DailyDine: Independent Reservation Engine
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        An architectural study on transaction serializability, offline recovery, and self-contained scheduling.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Context -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Context</h2>
        <p>
          DailyDine is a self-contained reservation system designed to allow local venues to accept bookings directly on their own websites.
          By avoiding commission-charging directories, venues retain absolute ownership over customer contact lists and operational databases.
          The project was initiated to build a lightweight, self-hosted API service capable of running on low-resource virtual private servers.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Constraints -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Constraints</h2>
        <p>
          The service must run stably on a single CPU core with less than 512MB of RAM, limiting execution footprint.
          Since reservation entries represent actual table seats, double-booking is a critical system failure.
          The scheduler must prevent overlapping reservations under heavy concurrent traffic, operating with zero room for state errors.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Alternatives Considered -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Alternatives Considered</h2>
        <p>
          We initially evaluated using a central in-memory store like Redis to coordinate reservation locks before database insertion.
          This pattern requires managing connection pool drops, matching key expiries to request timeouts, and writing failover logs.
          We also considered using application-level mutexes in Go.
          However, Go mutexes fail when scaling the API across multiple server instances behind a load balancer.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          We traded real-time UI synchronization via persistent WebSockets for client-side short polling and strict transaction isolates.
          While WebSockets provide instant updates, maintaining thousands of idle connections increases memory overhead.
          Short polling increases network log volume slightly but makes client state recovery completely predictable.
          We traded visual latency animations for server-side simplicity and memory safety.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Failures -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Failures</h2>
        <p>
          Our first scheduling database schema allowed overlapping reservation blocks and relied on application logic to validate bounds.
          Under simulated high-traffic loads, concurrent requests bypassed application validations due to race conditions.
          This resulted in duplicate bookings.
          We resolved this failure by replacing application-level logic with Postgres exclusion constraints using the btree_gist extension.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Monitoring -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Monitoring</h2>
        <p>
          To maintain visibility without bloated dashboard agents, we set up structured JSON logging in Go.
          Logs are written directly to stdout and collected by system daemons.
          We track metrics for API response latencies, database transaction rollbacks, and active database connection pool counts.
          Alerts trigger immediately if rollback rates exceed 2% within a five-minute window.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Scaling Considerations -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Scaling Considerations</h2>
        <p>
          As the platform grows, PostgreSQL disk reads during coordinate indexing can bottleneck execution.
          To scale lookup speeds, we partitioned reservation tables by month and created partial indexes for active reservation blocks.
          Additionally, static layouts and customer assets are cached at CDN edges, routing only booking actions to the database.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- If I Rebuilt It Today -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">If I Rebuilt It Today</h2>
        <p>
          If I started over, I would bypass application-level validation entirely from day one.
          Relying on database-level constraints is far more reliable and easier to test.
          I would also choose SQLite with WAL mode for smaller venues.
          This would completely remove database server administration overhead while maintaining transaction safety.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Public Roadmap -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pt-6">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Public Roadmap</h2>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6 text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] pt-2">
          <div>
            <span class="font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] block mb-1">Current Milestone</span>
            Optimizing partial indexes for multi-table seating configurations.
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] block mb-1">Next Milestone</span>
            Implementing encrypted JSON backup exports for offline archiving.
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] block mb-1">Risks & Unknowns</span>
            Managing locks during long-running transactional reports.
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] block mb-1">Recent Decisions</span>
            Deleted Redis coordination layer in favor of PostgreSQL serializable locks.
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Source Code -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.06)] pt-6">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Source Code</h2>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs font-mono">
          <a href="https://github.com/programmer-nick234/dailydine" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#2563EB] hover:underline">
            GitHub Repository
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: Go · React · PostgreSQL · Tailwind CSS · TypeScript</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
